 of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Danby in North Yorkshire, originally named in Old Norse as <i>Danabȳ</i> ‘settlement of the Danes’, and thus cognate with   Denby  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denby","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places so named in Yorkshire. A cognate of   Danby  , ‘settlement of the Danes’, but here the Old Norse first element has been replaced by the cognate Old English <i>Dene</i>."]},{"name":"Dansby","meanings":["English: presumably a habitational name from a lost or unidentified place in an area of Scandinavian settlement; perhaps a variant of   Danby  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Danby was born about 1350, in Danby, Yorkshire, England, his father, Robert Danbie I, was 21 and his mother, Lady Agnes de Grene, was 10. He married Mary Tanfield in 1402, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1398–1474":"1398–1474","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1474":"1474","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Bedale, Yorkshire, England":"Bedale, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Danby, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1350–":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1398–1474":"1398–1474","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1474":"1474","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","about 1350":"noin 1350","Bedale, Yorkshire, England":"Bedale, Yorkshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Danby, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1350–":"environ 1350–Décédé","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1398–1474":"1398–1474","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1474":"1474","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","about 1350":"environ 1350","Bedale, Yorkshire, England":"Bedale, Everwyck, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Danby, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Thomas Danby est né environ 1350, à Danby,